<dl id="n17065g"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n17" href="#n17065g">N17 (VI.B.9)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n17all.htm#n17065g"> 65(g)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> la puanteur / (mort <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n17065g"><li>FW 192.24 </li><li><a href="../../flex/g/lexg.htm#n17065g">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/g/l39g.htm#n17065g">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n17065g">MS BL 47474-69</ms> </li><li>JJA 47:447 <a name="gd4" href="../../FF/fdra/gda.htm#gd4">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/g/gd4.htm#n17065g">Draft: I.7&sect;1.4</a>/2.4</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Devenue m&egrave;re, mes occupations &eacute;taient le soin de mon enfant: la nuit, quand il pleurait, son p&egrave;re le portait doucement &agrave; mon sein; il partageait avec moi les travaux de son enfance. Nous &eacute;tions heureux, nous comptions toujours l&apos;&ecirc;tre. Un matin, je m&apos;aper&ccedil;us que l&apos;enfant &eacute;tait sans mouvement, nous jet&acirc;mes des cris horribles, nous ne savions pas que c&apos;&eacute;tait la mort; nous m&icirc;mes cet innocent entre nous deux pour le r&eacute;chauffer et le rappeler &agrave; la vie. Quelques jours apr&egrave;s l&apos;infection nous obligea de l&apos;&eacute;carter; la puanteur augmentant, nous l&apos;&eacute;loign&acirc;mes encore; et ne pouvant plus soutenir l&apos;infection du cadavre, nous le m&icirc;mes o&ugrave; &eacute;taient nos immondices. Chaque jour nous allions voir ce que devenait cet enfant. Une multitude d&apos;&ecirc;tre sortis de son corps nous surprirent; quelque temps apr&egrave;s, nous ne v&icirc;mes plus que les os. Cet &eacute;v&eacute;nement nous donna de l&apos;inqui&eacute;tude; nous ne pouvions comprendre pourquoi l&apos;enfant &eacute;tait dans cet &eacute;tat, pourquoi il avait pass&eacute; si subitement de la vie &agrave; la <mark>mort</mark>, que nous appellions <mark>la puanteur</mark>. <font color="green">[Becoming a mother, my occupations were the care of my child: at night, when he cried, his father carried him gently to my bosom; he shared with me the work of his childhood. We were happy, we were still counting it. One morning I noticed that the child was motionless, we uttered horrible cries, we did not know it was death; we put this innocent between us both to warm him up and call him back to life. A few days after the infection obliged us to dismiss it; the stench increasing, we pushed him away again; and being unable to sustain the infection of the corpse, we put it where our filth was. Every day we went to see what was happening to this child. A multitude of being out of his body surprised us; some time later we saw only the bones. This event gave us anxiety; we could not understand why the child was in this state, why he had so suddenly passed from life to death , that we called the stench .]</font> <small> Henri-Joseph Dulaurens, <a name="IMIR" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#IMIR"><cite title="source">Imirce ou la fille de la nature</cite></a> (1765, new ed. 1922) (?) 51</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Fr. <i>puanteur</i>: stench; <i>mort</i>: death.</mm> </dd></dl>
